<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Risbec" baseAuthorityYear="1928" class="Gastropoda" family="Pleurobranchidae" genus="Berthella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Berthella caledonica" order="Pleurobranchida" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="caledonica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Berthella caledonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from New Caledonia (
<bibRefCitation author="Risbec, J" journalOrPublisher="thesis, Universite de Paris, Paris" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" refId="B206" refString="Risbec, J, 1928. Contribution a l'etude des nudibranches Neo-Caledoniens. Faune des Colonies Francaises, 2: 1-328. Ph.D. thesis, Universite de Paris, Paris" title="Contribution a l'etude des nudibranches Neo-Caledoniens. Faune des Colonies Francaises, 2: 1 - 328. Ph. D." year="1928">Risbec 1928</bibRefCitation>
), Mariana Islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Carlson, C" journalOrPublisher="Micronesica" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="271 - 293" refId="B43" refString="Carlson, C, Hoff, P, 2003. The opisthobranchs of the Mariana Islands. Micronesica 35: 271 - 293" title="The opisthobranchs of the Mariana Islands." volume="35" year="2003">Carlson and Hoff 2003</bibRefCitation>
), Hawaii (
<bibRefCitation author="Johnson, S" journalOrPublisher="Check List" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" publicationUrl="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/7898" refId="B126" refString="Johnson, S, 2002a. Berthella cf. africana from Hawaii. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney. http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/7898" title="Berthella cf. africana from Hawaii. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney." url="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/7898" year="2002 a">Johnson 2002a</bibRefCitation>
), Marshall Islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Johnson, S" journalOrPublisher="Check List" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" publicationUrl="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/7899" refId="B127" refString="Johnson, S, 2002b. Berthella cf. africana from the Marshall Islands. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney. http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/7899" title="Berthella cf. africana from the Marshall Islands. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney." url="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/7899" year="2002 b">Johnson 2002b</bibRefCitation>
), Australia (
<bibRefCitation author="Cobb, GC" journalOrPublisher="Planta" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" publicationUrl="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/22062" refId="B53" refString="Cobb, GC, 2009. Pleurobranchus caledonicus found in sthn Queensland. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney. http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/22062" title="Pleurobranchus caledonicus found in sthn Queensland. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney." url="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/22062" year="2009">Cobb 2009</bibRefCitation>
), and Japan (
<bibRefCitation author="Bolland, B" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Bombay Natural History Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" publicationUrl="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/8024" refId="B26" refString="Bolland, B, 2002. Okinawa Berthella cf. africana. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney. http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/8024" title="Okinawa Berthella cf. africana. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney." url="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/8024" year="2002">Bolland 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
Overall colour variable from pink to light or dark brown, with numerous small, low tubercles across the dorsal surface, often surrounded by a brown ring, and with dark brown apices. A prominent brown mark surrounded by a diffuse ring of translucent white is located centrally on the dorsal surface. While specimens from Koh Tao resemble the description of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Risbec" baseAuthorityYear="1928" class="Gastropoda" family="Pleurobranchidae" genus="Berthella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Berthella caledonica" order="Pleurobranchida" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="caledonica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Berthella caledonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Risbec, 1928) rather well, records of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pruvot-Fol" baseAuthorityYear="1953" class="Gastropoda" family="Pleurobranchidae" genus="Berthella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Berthella africana" order="Pleurobranchida" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="africana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Berthella africana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Pruvot-Fol, 1956) have also been made from Thailand, with an unclear locality (
<bibRefCitation author="Nabhitabhata, J" journalOrPublisher="Office of Natural Resources and Environmental Policy and Planning, Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment, Bangkok" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" refId="B171" refString="Nabhitabhata, J, 2009. Checklist of Mollusca Fauna in Thailand. Office of Natural Resources and Environmental Policy and Planning, Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment, Bangkok" title="Checklist of Mollusca Fauna in Thailand." year="2009">Nabhitabhata 2009</bibRefCitation>
). Both species share external similarities, in particular the presence of a brown spot or 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘hole’">'hole'</normalizedToken>
found centrally on the dorsum, and the need for clarification between both species has been noted (
<bibRefCitation author="Gosliner, TM" journalOrPublisher="Sea Challengers Natural History Books, Gig Harbor" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" refId="B94" refString="Gosliner, TM, Behrens, D, Valdes, A, 2008. Indo-Pacific nudibranchs and sea slugs: a field guide to the world's most diverse fauna. Sea Challengers Natural History Books, Gig Harbor" title="Indo-Pacific nudibranchs and sea slugs: a field guide to the world's most diverse fauna." year="2008">Gosliner et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Rudman, WB" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Molluscan Studies" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" publicationUrl="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/pleucale" refId="B223" refString="Rudman, WB, 2009b. Pleurobranchus caledonicus Risbec, 1928. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney. http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/pleucale" title="Pleurobranchus caledonicus Risbec, 1928. Sea Slug Forum, Australian Museum, Sydney." url="http://www.seaslugforum.net/find/pleucale" year="2009 b">Rudman 2009b</bibRefCitation>
). The present species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Pleurobranchidae" genus="Berthella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Berthella" order="Pleurobranchida" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Berthella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 1 of 
<bibRefCitation author="Gosliner, TM" journalOrPublisher="New World Publications Inc., Jacksonville" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" refId="B96" refString="Gosliner, TM, Valdes, A, Behrens, D, 2018. Nudibranch &amp; Sea Slug Identification - Indo-Pacific. New World Publications Inc., Jacksonville" title="Nudibranch &amp; Sea Slug Identification - Indo-Pacific." year="2018">Gosliner et al. (2018)</bibRefCitation>
. With the Gulf of Thailand being distant from the type localities of both species (Morocco for 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. africana" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="africana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">B. africana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and New Caledonia for 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. caledonica" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="caledonica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">B. caledonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and the Pacific range currently known for 
<taxonomicName genus="B." lsidName="B. caledonica" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="caledonica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">B. caledonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the present species is treated as potentially distinct until such a time as closer examinations can be made.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
